  "id": "019d38ad-3bee-7bf2-b248-905ba3f17796",
  "content": "# Content Voice and Tone Preferences — Lim Chun Zhe (2026-03-29)\n\nLearned during the 27-day reflection post collaboration. These preferences apply to all future LinkedIn posts, carousels, and public-facing content.\n\n## Tone and Framing\n\n- **Humble, not arrogant.** Never frame things as \"I didn't expect this to work so well.\" Instead: \"I didn't expect it to be ready yet.\" The surprise is at the tool, not at the reader.\n- **Honest about imperfections.** Not everything ships perfectly. Still learning AI-assisted development. Say it directly. Readers respect authenticity over polish.\n- **Let it breathe.** Don't condense so much that it feels rushed. If a beat deserves 3 sentences, give it 3 sentences. Longer is fine for reflection pieces.\n- **Context before examples.** Don't drop specific scenarios (like \"auth system redesigned across three repos\") without first explaining what category of thing it is. Set up the concept, then give the concrete example.\n- **Jokes land as jokes, not complaints.** \"When they ran the 2x token promotion, I was out diving and missed most of it. Timing. hahaha\" — light, self-deprecating. Never frame constraints as grievances.\n- **\"hahaha\" is acceptable.** Casual laughter is part of the voice. Don't sanitize it.\n\n## Perspective and Identity\n\n- **Always intended as a product.** corvia was never \"just a portfolio project that accidentally became real.\" It was always intended as a real product. The portfolio aspect is the job-search context, not the identity.\n- **Portable development tool.** A core motivation: owning your own dev tool that travels with you across roles and projects. Every role change = wasted time rebuilding env. corvia solves that.\n- **Job seeker context.** Currently looking for next role. This grounds the story. Open and close with it when appropriate. Not ashamed. #OpenToWork.\n- **Left previous role, started immediately.** Friday was last day, started building that weekend. Don't over-emphasize but it shows drive.\n- **Learning GenAI firsthand.** Started corvia partly to understand generative AI by building in it, not just reading about it. Hands-on >> blog posts. This is a core belief.\n\n## What NOT to frame as selling points\n\n- **Zero-dependency is not a theme.** The user loves Docker. The devcontainer uses Docker. Don't frame \"no Docker needed\" as a win.\n- **\"Portfolio to product\" is not the arc.** Always intended as a product from day one.\n- **Speed/velocity is not the main story.** 382 commits in 27 days is impressive but it's context, not the headline.\n\n## What to highlight\n\n- **Dogfooding pride.** Using corvia to build corvia is the emotional core. But be honest: it wasn't available day 1. There was a bootstrap phase with markdown files.\n- **The loop evolved gradually.** Day 1 was brainstorm + design + build. The 5-persona review, session history, agent coordination came later. Some early decisions got missed. The process and product co-evolved.\n- **Grabbing emerging capabilities.** When Claude ships Agent Teams, immediately build an adapter. When GitNexus appears, start building structural intelligence. The mindset: AI moves fast, grab every capability and build on it. That's how you stay on edge.\n- **Claude convergence = exciting.** When major players build in the same direction, it validates the problem. Not threatening. Complementary. Personal memory is table stakes. Organizational layer is still open.\n- **Real-world validation.** Interview take-home finished in <24 hours using corvia methodology. First test outside corvia's own development. The methodology transferred.\n- **Features not fully internalized yet.** Many recent capabilities are built and tested but not fully used. It takes time as a human to understand how tools change your workflow. This is an honest, relatable insight.\n- **Claude Max 5 constraint.** Not cheap when unemployed, but committed. Play it light, not as a complaint.\n\n## Style Rules\n\n- No em dashes. Use periods and short sentences.\n- No \"surprised me\" hooks. Prefer \"interesting\" for discoveries.\n- Show-don't-tell with specific numbers and concrete details.\n- End with an engagement question.\n- Reference carousel slides in the post text.\n- Carousel feature showcases should be clean and impactful, not cluttered. Group capabilities into pillars with taglines.",
